  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Southern Sudan Community Schools Programme</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The conflict in South Sudan meant that many children missed out on years of schooling. There are insufficient school places for all the children who need them and many children are put off going to school by threats of violence from other children, corporal punishment from teachers, or the lack of basic facilities like toilets. Girls, orphans and disabled children are particularly vulnerable to missing out on an education. BRAC UK runs a programme of one-room schools in a number of remote areas. Children are taught in a special room set aside in their communities, by women who come from their area and who are trained how to teach by the project. As a result, many children and young people are given a chance to have an education, which they could never otherwise have enjoyed. Afterwards, they can continue with their education by joining government schools, take up vocational training, or start small businesses. The project can lead to life-changing opportunities for the children and young people affected.</narrative>
  </description>
